  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "ExhCFxEmHSSJSP8jqbnDBmI68nE=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:27.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "**ADR-002: Extract StampManager and ShareManager from SwarmClient**\n\n**Status:** Accepted (2026-04-10)\n\n**Context:** `SwarmClient` had grown to 1,035 lines with ~30 methods covering 10 responsibilities \u2014 data CRUD, feeds, stamps, pricing, sharing, profiles, ACT, compaction, and more. The class became hard to test and reason about.\n\n**Decision:** Extract two focused classes:\n\n- `StampManager` \u2014 stamp lifecycle and pricing.\n- `ShareManager` \u2014 profiles, sharing, and key derivation.\n\n`SwarmClient` keeps thin delegation methods pointing at these managers so existing call sites continue to work.\n\n**Consequences:**\n- Positive: `SwarmClient` refocuses on core CRUD + feeds + manifests and drops to 531 lines.\n- Positive: `StampManager` and `ShareManager` become independently unit-testable.\n- Negative: delegation wrappers add a layer of indirection that readers must follow.\n\nADR-003 (same date) complements this by adding optional DI parameters (e.g. `bee: Bee` on `SwarmClient`, `provider: EthereumProvider` on `wallet-signer`) so all three classes can be constructed with injected mocks and tested without global patching.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:27.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:27.000Z"
    }
  },
